"We still had good chances and a blatant penalty when Kieran [Smith] has gone through and has been pulled back.
"They had two chances in the first half and that's the difference at this level. It's a bit frustrating really... we have had the better chances.
"If we get the first goal out there, it's an away goal and they will be in a sticky situation.
"They were panicking towards the end here.
"It just frustrates me we have done ever so well but you have to take the chances at this level."

The teenager is charged with supplying drugs in East Calder , where police are investigating the death of 15 - year - old Dione Melville . Emergency services were called to a house in the town on Sunday morning , but the teenager was pronounced dead at the scene shortly after their arrival.

Police Scotland confirmed that a 17-year-old male has been arrested and charged in connection with supplying controlled drugs and is due to appear at Livingston Sheriff Court. The investigation into Dione’s death is ongoing, with a post-mortem examination scheduled to determine the exact cause.

Dione, a popular pupil at St John's Academy in Livingston, has been widely remembered by friends and family. Tributes have poured in on social media, expressing shock and sadness. A family statement described her as "our beautiful girl, who was loved by everyone." Lisa Grubb, a close family member, posted a heartfelt tribute online, urging young people to be aware of drug dangers.

Chief Inspector Alistair Leitch, Local Area Commander, said: "Our thoughts are with Dione's family. We understand the East Calder community will be deeply affected. A thorough investigation is underway, and we are following several lines of enquiry."

Police appeal for anyone with information to contact Police Scotland via 101, quoting the incident number. The community remains in shock as details unfold.

Pte Sean Benton was found dead at the Surrey barracks with five gunshot wounds in June 1995 , while on guard at a perimeter fence . Human rights group Liberty said the Attorney General had given his family consent to apply to the High Court . An earlier inquest recorded a verdict of suicide on the 20 - year - old soldier . The coroner at a second inquest on Pte Cheryl James , who died at Deepcut in 1995, concluded in 2016 that her death was not suicide but an 'unlawful killing', a landmark overturning of the original finding. Pte James was one of four young soldiers who died from gunshot wounds at the Princess Royal Barracks, Deepcut, in Surrey, between 1995 and 2002. The others were Private Geoff Gray, Private James Collinson, and Private Kevin Williams. All four deaths were initially ruled as suicides, leading to years of tenacious campaigning by their families, who consistently maintained that the circumstances surrounding their children's deaths were suspicious and that the original investigations were fundamentally flawed.

The tragic sequence of Deepcut deaths became a national scandal, shining a harsh light on welfare provisions, alleged bullying, and the duty of care within the British Army. Families, often supported by organisations such as Liberty, fought tirelessly to have the original inquest verdicts quashed and new inquiries launched, believing that vital evidence had been overlooked or mishandled. The case of Pte Cheryl James, in particular, gained renewed traction when her parents, Des and Doreen James, secured a fresh inquest following years of arduous legal battles. This second inquest heard compelling evidence of a pervasive culture of fear, harassment, and even alleged sexual exploitation at the barracks, which her family powerfully argued contributed directly to her death.

Similarly, the family of Pte Sean Benton, also found dead at the same Deepcut Barracks in Surrey, has long sought a new inquest into his death. His sister, Tracy Lewis, and other family members have consistently challenged the original suicide verdict, citing numerous inconsistencies in the evidence and a disturbing lack of proper investigation at the time. The recent consent granted by the Attorney General for Pte Benton's family to apply to the High Court for a fresh inquest underscores the profound and ongoing concerns about the integrity of the original inquiries into these tragic deaths.

These landmark cases, driven by the extraordinary persistence and courage of the bereaved families and their dedicated legal teams, have had a profound and lasting impact on the understanding of military deaths and the standards of investigation within the armed forces. They have critically highlighted the urgent need for independent oversight and a transparent justice process when service personnel die in non-combat circumstances. The re-examination of these deeply troubling cases, particularly through the High Court and subsequent new inquests, represents a pivotal moment in the collective quest for truth and accountability, offering a glimmer of hope for long-awaited closure to families who have endured decades of anguish and unanswered questions regarding the deaths of their loved ones at Deepcut and similar military establishments.

James Percival , 66 , said he gave mouth - to - mouth resuscitation to newborn Jonathan Percival in the vicarage in Freckleton , Lancashire , in 2014 . But Ruth Percival , 30 , said she had not seen him make any attempts to revive the baby . The inquest was halted in October when new medical evidence led the coroner to refer the case to prosecutors . In March , the Crown Prosecution Service said there remained " insufficient evidence to pursue a prosecution against anyone in connection with Jonathan's death. This decision meant that the coroner, Dr. James Adeley, could now resume the inquest into the circumstances surrounding the infant's passing. The hearing, which had initially begun in October of the previous year, aimed to establish the medical cause of death for Jonathan Percival, who was just 36 hours old when he died at the vicarage in Freckleton.

During earlier sessions, disturbing details had emerged, including the starkly contrasting accounts from James Percival and Ruth Percival. James Percival, who claimed to have delivered the baby, maintained that he had attempted to resuscitate the infant, performing mouth-to-mouth and chest compressions. He described the baby as being born "blue" and not breathing, prompting his immediate intervention. However, Ruth Percival, the child's mother, presented a vastly different narrative. She testified that she was in the room throughout the critical period and did not observe James Percival making any efforts to revive Jonathan. Her testimony cast serious doubt on his account of the events leading up to the baby's death.

The new medical evidence that prompted the coroner to involve prosecutors was not publicly detailed but was understood to have raised specific questions about the circumstances of Jonathan's death and the care he received. Despite this, the CPS concluded that the evidential threshold for criminal charges could not be met. The family of Jonathan Percival, including Ruth Percival, expressed their ongoing desire for a full understanding of what happened to the newborn. The resumed inquest was expected to hear further expert medical testimony and revisit the conflicting accounts from James Percival and Ruth Percival, with the coroner's ultimate goal being to provide a definitive conclusion on the cause and circumstances of Jonathan's tragic death in Freckleton, Lancashire. The legal proceedings continue to bring to light the complexities and emotional toll of the case for all involved, particularly the parents seeking answers.

The National Environment Research Council defended its decision to hold a public poll to suggest names , in which Boaty McBoatface got the most support . Professor Duncan Wingham said the row had " put a smile " on people 's faces . But MPs asked if he would be made to " walk the plank " by ministers , who The National Environment Research Council defended its decision to hold a public poll to suggest names , in which Boaty McBoatface got the most support . Professor Duncan Wingham said the row had " put a smile " on people 's faces . But MPs asked if he would be made to " walk the plank " by ministers, who were perturbed by the public outcry and ridicule. Despite the clear poll outcome, the National Environment Research Council decided against naming its new £200 million polar research vessel RRS Boaty McBoatface.

Instead, it was named RRS Sir David Attenborough, a choice reflecting its serious scientific mission and vital role in understanding global environmental changes. This sparked widespread public anger and accusations that the NERC had disregarded the democratic will, leading to social media uproar over the perceived hypocrisy.

Prof Wingham, while facing scrutiny, defended the NERC's stance, arguing a more dignified name was essential for a vessel undertaking critical polar and climate research. To appease the public, NERC announced a compromise: a remotely operated underwater vehicle (ROV) on the RRS Sir David Attenborough would be named ‘Boaty McBoatface’. This solution allowed the beloved name to be incorporated into the scientific mission, ensuring its quirky legacy endured. The saga became a memorable case study in public engagement, forever linking Prof Wingham and the National Environment Research Council with Boaty McBoatface.

Halfpenny 's Toulon club coach Richard Cockerill was reportedly trying to negotiate the release of the fullback for the Top 14 final on June 4 if the French side reached the showpiece . But Gatland ruled out the prospect and says the schedule is clear . " He will be with us for the entirety of the British & Irish Lions training camp," Gatland stated unequivocally. "The schedule is set, and it's clear. All players are expected to be available from the very beginning." This firm stance highlights Gatland's unwavering commitment to player availability for the crucial tour preparations, which he views as non-negotiable for team cohesion and strategic development. The Lions squad, including key figures like Halfpenny, is due to assemble for their pre-tour camp on May 22, just under two weeks before the proposed Top 14 final. For Gatland, every moment of preparation is invaluable, especially with a demanding schedule of ten matches, including three Tests against the world champions, New Zealand.

The head coach has consistently emphasised that the integrity of the Lions tour takes absolute precedence, and that all selected players must be fully committed and present for the duration of the build-up. This policy has been a clear one from the start of the selection process. The coaching staff believes that any early absences would severely compromise the team’s ability to gel and perform at the elite level required to challenge the All Blacks on their home turf. Halfpenny, renowned for his defensive prowess, accurate goal-kicking, and strong counter-attacking game, is considered a vital component of Gatland's plans. His experience from previous Lions tours, particularly the victorious 2013 series in Australia, makes his early integration into the squad even more paramount. Richard Cockerill's attempts to secure Leigh Halfpenny’s release for such a significant club fixture are understandable from Toulon's perspective. However, Gatland's firm refusal reinforces the unique status and demands of the British & Irish Lions tour, which operates outside the usual club-versus-country dynamics. The focus is now squarely on preparing Leigh and the rest of the squad for the formidable challenge in New Zealand.

Mohammed Abdurezek, who had links to Swansea and Newcastle, was found with several stab wounds by a dog-walker in Siston, South Gloucestershire.
A post-mortem examination revealed the 31-year-old died from multiple stab wounds.
The three men, one aged 42 and two 22, remain in custody, an Avon and Somerset Police spokesman said.

Mencap and the Challenging Behaviour Foundation have spoken of the risks of moving patients hundreds of miles . The warning comes as the results of a serious case review into the abuse of patients at the private hospital near Bristol are due to be released . The abuse was uncovered during secret filming by the BBC Panorama programme . Eleven people have admitted charges of ill - treatment and neglect related to the abuse . South Gloucestershire Safeguarding Adults Board ( SAB ) commissioned the review , carried out by an independent investigator. The review meticulously examined the systemic failures allowing horrific abuse at Winterbourne View, the private hospital near Bristol. It delved into circumstances leading to patients being placed far from families and communities, a key concern highlighted by Mencap and the Challenging Behaviour Foundation. Their long-standing campaigns consistently warned against inherent risks of distant placements, which isolate vulnerable individuals, hinder family visits, and create environments where neglect and abuse are less likely to be detected.

The serious case review, commissioned by the SAB, sought to identify not only direct perpetrators but also broader institutional and commissioning failures. It scrutinised oversight mechanisms, or lack thereof, from local authorities and NHS trusts responsible for patient placement at Winterbourne View. Findings are expected to be stark, revealing how a system designed to protect vulnerable adults failed them catastrophically. The BBC Panorama exposé, using secret filming to uncover shocking abuse, served as a crucial catalyst, forcing a national reckoning with care quality for people with learning disabilities and challenging behaviour in residential settings.

The eleven individuals who admitted charges related to ill-treatment and neglect represent a tragic failure of individual responsibility, but the review's scope goes far beyond individual culpability. It aims to provide recommendations to prevent such atrocities. These are anticipated to include a significant shift away from large institutional placements towards smaller, community-based care closer to homes and families. Strong calls are likely for improved regulation, robust inspection regimes, and enhanced staff training. Furthermore, the review is expected to highlight the critical need for better communication between care providers, commissioning bodies, and families, ensuring concerns are heard and acted upon promptly.

Mencap and the Challenging Behaviour Foundation have advocated for comprehensive reform, pushing for person-centred care prioritizing individual rights, dignity, and access to a full life within their community. Their warnings about perils of out-of-area placements, often driven by lack of appropriate local provision or cost-saving, have been tragically vindicated by Winterbourne View. The SAB's commitment to releasing the full findings of this independent review demonstrates a crucial step towards transparency and accountability. Lessons from this harrowing episode must drive genuine, lasting change across health and social care sectors, ensuring safeguarding of vulnerable adults remains paramount. The imperative is to learn from systemic failures and implement robust measures to protect those who rely on specialist care, preventing any recurrence of neglect and abuse. The review's findings will undoubtedly inform national policy and practice, reinforcing the urgent need for a fundamental shift in how care is commissioned and delivered for individuals with complex needs, moving from isolated institutional settings towards inclusive, community-based support.

The decision was taken despite the 26 - year - old running the Olympic qualifying time on six occasions and coming third in the trials . " I accept I will never win an Olympic medal , " she wrote on eightlane.org . UK Athletics said they do not respond to individual selection decisions, a stance that has often led to frustration among athletes vying for Olympic berths. The 26-year-old athlete in question was Shelayna Oskan-Clarke, whose omission from the initial women's 800m squad for the Games sparked considerable debate within the athletics community. Despite her consistent form and meeting the stringent qualifying standard multiple times, Oskan-Clarke's third-place finish at the national trials did not guarantee her a spot, as UK Athletics' selection policy allows for discretionary picks beyond the top two automatic qualifiers. This controversial approach meant that while Lynsey Sharp, another strong contender, secured her place, the final slot remained a point of contention. Oskan-Clarke’s powerful statement on eightlane.org highlighted the immense psychological toll such uncertainty and perceived injustice can take on athletes who dedicate their lives to their sport. Her public lament resonated with many who felt the selection process lacked transparency and fairness, especially given her demonstrated ability to compete at the highest level. The incident underscored ongoing concerns about the subjective nature of some selection criteria, which can leave athletes feeling vulnerable and disempowered, their Olympic dreams hinging on decisions that often seem inexplicable. While UK Athletics maintains its right to select the strongest possible team, the lack of detailed explanations for controversial omissions continues to be a source of tension between the governing body and its athletes.

The common riding season got under way in the Borders on Friday with the horses out in Hawick.
The 2017 Cornet Ali George and his Lass Katy Moffat led proceedings through the town.
Hawick is one of a number of Borders towns to hold such celebrations throughout the summer months.
They see a horseback group ride its way around the town's historic boundaries as part of the ceremony.

Fancy 's Farm in Portland is asking for discarded trees to feed to the eager goats. Farm manager Sue Illsley is spearheading the initiative, noting that the trees offer essential enrichment and a much-needed dietary supplement for the herd, especially during the colder months. It's a sustainable way to repurpose your old Christmas tree and help the farm's beloved goats.

The Met Office issued at yellow " be aware " warning of the conditions at 08:45 for the Highlands and parts of Aberdeenshire and central Scotland . The warning of ice and snow falling to about an inch ( 4 cm ) on ground will persist throughout the day, particularly impacting higher ground and untreated surfaces. The Met Office has advised that these conditions are likely to lead to some difficult driving conditions on many routes across Aberdeenshire, central Scotland, and the Highlands. Motorists are urged to exercise extreme caution, allow extra time for journeys, and consider if their travel is essential. Particular concern has been raised for major arteries such as the A9, A90, and the A82, where strong winds could also lead to drifting snow and reduced visibility, making conditions treacherous. Public transport services, including bus and rail, may also experience delays or cancellations as a result of the challenging weather. Local authorities in Scotland are working to ensure priority routes are gritted, but secondary roads and rural areas are expected to be most affected. The yellow warning is expected to remain in place until at least midnight on Friday, with further updates from the Met Office anticipated as the situation develops. Residents in affected areas are encouraged to check local news and weather forecasts regularly for the latest information and to prepare for potential disruptions to daily routines. Schools in some remote parts of Aberdeenshire have already announced closures or delayed openings. The advice is to dress warmly, carry emergency supplies in vehicles, and avoid unnecessary travel, especially during peak snowfall periods. The combination of falling snow, freezing rain, and high winds creates a significant hazard for drivers and pedestrians alike throughout Scotland, emphasizing the need for vigilance on all routes.

Afghanistan 's intelligence agency blamed Wednesday 's attack on militants allegedly backed by Islamabad . An Afghanistan Cricket Board ( ACB ) statement it could not agree to play against " a country where terrorists are housed and provided safe havens " . The Pakistan Cricket Board ( PCB ) later accused the ACB of " playing politics " . Pakistan has rejected an Afghan claim that it was involved the attack The unprecedented decision by the Afghanistan Cricket Board (ACB) to halt cricketing ties underscores escalating diplomatic tensions between Kabul and Islamabad. This dramatic move threatens to derail a planned T20 series and future bilateral engagements, as the ACB declared it could not play against "a country where terrorists are housed and provided safe havens." The Pakistan Cricket Board (PCB) quickly hit back, accusing the ACB of "playing politics" and lamenting the politicization of sports. "Cricket should unite people, not divide them," a PCB official reportedly stated, emphasizing the sport's traditional spirit.

The PCB further highlighted its historical role in nurturing Afghan talent, with many Afghan cricketers gaining crucial experience through Pakistan's domestic leagues and the Pakistan Super League (PSL). This cricketing bridge, built over years of shared passion, now appears severely damaged. From Afghanistan's perspective, however, the direct link established by its intelligence agencies between the recent attack and elements allegedly operating from Pakistani soil makes normal sporting exchanges untenable. The ACB’s statement reflects a broader national sentiment demanding accountability and an end to what Kabul views as cross-border terrorism. The Afghan government has consistently accused Islamabad of supporting militant groups that destabilize Afghanistan, a charge Pakistan vehemently denies, asserting its own struggles with terrorism originating from across the border.

The impasse poses a significant challenge for the future of cricket between the two nations. The diplomatic fallout from the attack is thus casting a long shadow over any prospects of immediate reconciliation, not just in politics but also on the cricket field. The Afghanistan Cricket Board’s defiant stance, backed by the Afghan government, signals that until Afghanistan perceives a tangible shift in Islamabad's policy regarding alleged militant safe havens, the sporting arena will remain inextricably linked to their deeply entrenched political grievances. The Pakistan Cricket Board continues to advocate for the separation of sports and politics, but without a resolution to the underlying security concerns, the future of cricket between these passionate rivals remains highly uncertain.

The 31-year-old Australian was hurt during the Chiefs' narrow Champions Cup loss at Ulster and needs surgery.
Salvi joined the Chiefs in the summer of 2015 from Leicester and became a key part of the side that made last season's Premiership final.
"We're still waiting to learn the full extent of it but it looks relatively serious," head coach Rob Baxter said.
Salvi was twice short-listed for the Premiership's Player of the Year award while at Leicester and is a former Australia Under-21 captain.
"He does put in a huge contribution over 80 minutes, and that's probably what we'll miss the most," Baxter told BBC Sport.
"His biggest quality is his consistency. He turns up every week, and even when we've had some poor performances and even when some individuals within the side have played poorly, Julian's contribution has always been absolutely first rate," added Baxter.
"He's virtually always our top tackler, virtually always our top clearout guy, and probably the thing that people don't appreciate about him is how important he is to our attack.
"A lot of people talk about open-sides as being tacklers and defenders and disruptive people, but Julian is very important to our attack because he clears so many breakdowns."

The company has " paused " production at its Redcar blast furnace blaming a slump in demand and rising costs . SSI took over the former Tata Steel complex after it was mothballed in 2010 and employs almost 2,000 people . Ms Soubry said EU rules meant state cash could not be directly used to support British steel production . SSI UK Business Director Cornelius Louwrens said the move was 'extremely disappointing' but 'absolutely essential' given the challenging market conditions. He emphasized that the decision was taken to preserve the long-term viability of the business, exploring all options for its future. The Redcar plant, a symbol of industrial heritage in the North East, now faces an uncertain future, sparking fears for the jobs of its almost 2,000 workers and the wider supply chain. Trade unions called for urgent government intervention, arguing that the closure would be a devastating blow to the region and the UK's manufacturing capacity. Despite Ms Soubry's comments on EU restrictions, pressure is mounting on ministers to find a solution that could save the iconic steelworks. The company had previously warned about the impact of cheap imports and high energy costs, issues that have plagued the UK steel industry for years. The blast furnace, one of the largest in Europe, is a critical component of the integrated steelworks, and its shutdown effectively halts primary steelmaking on the site. The community, still recovering from previous closures under Tata Steel, watches anxiously as the fate of Redcar hangs in the balance, underscoring the broader challenges facing heavy industry in the UK.

Queen 's Lodge , Colwyn Bay , was the home of the first Lord Colwyn . It became two care homes following the death of Frederick Henry Smith , an industrialist and banker , in 1946 These care homes, still known to many locally as 'the lodge', continued to operate for several decades. They were later overseen by the Merseyside Hospitals Council, reflecting the significant post-war changes in healthcare provision across Wales. The substantial property eventually ceased its function as care homes, with its future use subject to various proposals over the years. Its historical and architectural significance, including its transformation from a grand private residence into multiple care facilities after Frederick Henry Smith's death, is comprehensively documented by the National Monuments Record of Wales. This record preserves the detailed history of the lodge and its evolving role within the community of Colwyn Bay, Wales.

Former WBA super - bantamweight champion Quigg would be closer to facing Wales ' Lee Selby if he wins on Saturday . " It 's a great opportunity for Scott , " said Quigg . "I've been working tirelessly for this chance. Lee Selby is a top-level operator, and a win against him would put me right back in the world title picture. But first, my focus is entirely on Saturday night. I cannot afford to look past my opponent; every fight is a stepping stone. I'm prepared for whatever he brings." Promoter Eddie Hearn has long eyed a domestic dust-up between Quigg and Selby, believing it would be a major draw for British boxing fans. "Both Scott and Lee are exceptional talents with huge followings," Hearn commented. "The public wants to see these big fights, and if Scott delivers on Saturday, that's definitely a match we'll be pushing hard for. It's a tantalizing prospect for Wales and indeed, all UK boxing." Quigg echoed Hearn's sentiments, emphasizing his readiness for the challenge. "I'm confident I'll get the job done on Saturday," he added. "Then, we can really start talking about Lee. I want the biggest fights, and he's one of them.

The 33-year-old forward began his career with Northampton, before spells with Mansfield, Lincoln and Chester.
He then scored 10 goals in 39 league games for Shrewsbury and secured a ¬£50,000 move to French side Nice, but joined Hamilton two years later.
The forward has since played in Bulgaria and most recently has been plying his trade in South Korea.
Asamoah, who will wear the number 25 shirt for Carlisle, has made four appearances for Ghana, scoring one goal.

Campaign group Liberty says the powers , which are used by intelligence agencies to collect large volumes of data from electronic devices , amount to an " assault on our freedom " . The Investigatory Powers Act gained royal assent in November . The government has said it will defend the act . Powers covered by the act allow state agencies to control and alter electronic devices , read texts , online messages and emails, monitor phone calls and access location data. This controversial legislation, dubbed the 'Snooper's Charter' by critics, grants extensive surveillance capabilities to agencies like MI5, MI6, and GCHQ. Liberty, with director Martha Spurrier at the forefront, argues the act constitutes an "assault on our freedom" by enabling mass surveillance. Spurrier contends it permits indiscriminate data collection on ordinary citizens, setting a dangerous precedent for civil liberties rather than targeting specific threats. She calls it one of the most extreme surveillance laws in a democracy. Despite significant opposition, including from the House of Lords which sought stronger privacy protections, the Investigatory Powers Act gained royal assent. The government, under then-Prime Minister Theresa May, defended the act as vital for national security in the digital age. May argued it merely updated existing powers, bringing transparency and proper oversight through independent judicial commissioners. However, Liberty and other privacy advocates continue to challenge its proportionality. They highlight concerns over bulk data collection, device hacking, and the requirement for internet service providers to retain browsing history for 12 months, viewing these as unacceptable intrusions. Legal challenges are anticipated, potentially reaching the European Court of Human Rights. The act underscores a fundamental tension between state security and individual freedoms, with critics warning of a chilling effect on free expression.

The 26 - year - old former SC Amiens , Rayo Vallecano and Dijon midfielder player can also operate effectively as a defensive midfielder or even in a more advanced playmaking role, demonstrating his versatility across the midfield. With experience gained from his time in France and Spain, he is now reportedly a target for English clubs, including MK Dons, as he looks for a new challenge. His time with SC Amiens, Rayo Vallecano and Dijon highlights a career of playing at competitive levels.

Thomas Groome , 53 , was last seen by his family in Thorne in Doncaster on New Year 's Day , 2010 . Jason Thaxter , of Hexthorpe , Doncaster , was convicted of murder and conspiracy to prevent a burial following a five - week trial . He was jailed at Sheffield Crown Court and ordered to serve a minimum of 17 years in prison before being considered for parole. Thomas Groome's disappearance on New Year's Day, 2010, from Thorne, Doncaster, sparked a major three-year investigation by South Yorkshire Police. Despite extensive searches, Mr Groome's body has never been found, a distressing fact that remained central throughout the entire legal process.

The five-week trial at Sheffield Crown Court heard how Jason Thaxter, from Hexthorpe, Doncaster, had brutally murdered Mr Groome and then taken deliberate steps to conceal his body, leading to the charge of conspiracy to prevent a burial. This absence of remains presented significant challenges for detectives, yet the prosecution successfully built a compelling case against Thaxter.

In sentencing, Judge Roger Thomas QC described Thaxter's actions as "callous and calculated," highlighting the immense and prolonged anguish caused to Mr Groome's family, who have been denied the opportunity to lay him to rest. South Yorkshire Police commended their team's perseverance in securing a conviction in this complex "no-body" murder case. Mr Groome's family continue to make heartfelt appeals for information regarding the location of his remains, hoping to finally bring him home and find some peace.

Profits at the technology giant were up 17% from the same period last year.
"Our devices and services transformation is progressing," said boss Steve Ballmer in a statement. He added that Microsoft is launching a "wide range" of new products in the coming quarter.
The report shed no light on who is to replace Mr Ballmer, who announced plans to retire within the next year.
The company has released several new products this quarter, including an update to Windows 8, and recently bought the mobile phone unit of struggling Finnish giant Nokia.
Shares rose 6% in after hours trading on the strong results.
For the first time, Microsoft also announced sales of its tablet computer, Surface.
It said revenues from Surface "grew to $400 million with sequential growth in revenue and units sold over the prior quarter".
Last quarter, the company was forced to take an embarrassing write down of $900m after sluggish sales.
The computer, well-liked by reviewers, marked Microsoft's first foray into hardware manufacturing.
However consumers, many of whom expressed displeasure at Microsoft's update to its popular operating system Windows, did not bite.
The company still did not provide sales figures of the device.
Investors hoping for any information about who will replace Mr Ballmer in the new year were disappointed.
Earlier today, on a conference call to discuss earnings, Ford boss Alan Mullaly declined to comment on rumours that he was being considered for the top job.
Other contenders include Stephen Elop, the former head of Nokia, who resigned as boss after Microsoft announced it would purchase the Nokia's mobile phone unit for 5.4bn euros ($7.2bn; ¬£4.6bn) in September.
Mr Elop is now head of Devices and Services at Nokia, although he is expected to transfer to Microsoft - where he was once a top manager - once the deal is completed.
Mr Ballmer has been at the helm of Microsoft since 2000, and has been at the company since 1980.

The talks come after Papua New Guinea's Supreme Court ruled the facility unconstitutional, overturning a deal reached between the governments.
Australia sends asylum seekers there under its offshore processing policy.
Papua New Guinea has now said it will close the facility, but it is not clear when that could happen.
Manus Island was first opened in 2001, and along with Australia's other offshore processing centres, has played a central role in Australia's controversial asylum policy.
Papua New Guinea's high commissioner to Australia Charles Lepani said the detainees were now Australia's responsibility, but Australia has remained opposed to taking any of them.
Immigration Minister Peter Dutton said on Thursday there was room for them at another detention centre on Nauru.
"There's capacity [on Nauru] but we're talking with the PNG government about what options are available in PNG and we'll continue those discussions with them," Mr Dutton said on Sky News.
This comes after an Iranian asylum seeker held at the Australian-funded detention centre on Nauru set himself on fire on Wednesday.
His actions were a "political protest" according to the Nauruan government.
Mr Dutton said the 23-year old man was in a serious condition and was evacuated to Australia for treatment.
Nauru is a small Pacific Island nation about 3,000 km (1,800 miles) north-east of Australia.
It was previously administered by Australia but gained independence in 1968.
What next for Manus Island asylum-seekers?
Manus Island: Australia's Guantanamo?
Australia's controversial asylum policy
Mr Dutton said that the man set himself on fire at a settlement outside the detention centre.
"He's in a very serious condition," Mr Dutton said.
"His outlook is not good at all."
He also confirmed that other asylum seekers held on the island had harmed themselves.
"What we've been very clear about is that if people come to Australia for medical assistance they'll be returning back to Nauru once that medical assistance has been provided.
"We have returned three people back to Nauru from Australia and they have returned because the medical assistance that they sought in Australia has been provided," Mr Dutton said.
Representatives from the refugee agency UNHCR were visiting Nauru when the incident occurred, he said.
An Iranian asylum seeker was last month fined for trying to kill himself during an attempt to move him and his daughter from the centre on Nauru.

The fine print of the deal suggests something slightly different , and shows that GM has in fact taken a hit of up to ¬£6bn in order to get shot of Vauxhall and Opel . First , a big chunk of the price - three - quarters of a billion pounds - is not for car plants , but for loans taken out by the owners of Opel and Vauxhall This unusual arrangement highlights that rather than simply selling an asset, GM is effectively paying to divest itself of a long-standing financial burden. The bulk of the £6bn charge, however, stems from the substantial pension liabilities that GM has chosen to retain rather than offload to Peugeot. Estimates place GM's retention of pension obligations for Vauxhall and Opel employees at well over £5bn, reflecting the enormous cost of legacy commitments built up over decades. This decision, made in Detroit, underscores GM's strategic imperative to clear its balance sheet of European losses that have plagued its financial performance for years. By retaining these liabilities, GM avoids the potentially complex and protracted negotiations that would have been required to transfer them to Peugeot, thereby expediting the sale and providing a clean break.

The deal, therefore, is less about GM selling a profitable division and more about a costly exit from a market where it has struggled to compete consistently. For Peugeot, this acquisition of Vauxhall and Opel presents an opportunity to significantly increase its market share in Europe and achieve substantial economies of scale. However, it also means inheriting a business that has been unprofitable for nearly two decades, requiring significant restructuring and investment to turn around. The challenge for Peugeot will be to integrate the Vauxhall and Opel operations efficiently, streamline production, and reduce costs without alienating the workforce or diluting the brands' appeal. The focus for Vauxhall under its new ownership will be on platform sharing with Peugeot models, standardizing components, and rationalizing the product portfolio to improve profitability. This move signals a definitive shift in GM's global strategy, allowing it to concentrate resources on more lucrative markets like North America and China, and invest heavily in future technologies such as electric and autonomous vehicles. The severance of ties with Vauxhall and Opel frees up capital and management attention, enabling GM to pursue its growth ambitions elsewhere, even if the price of freedom came with a hefty £6bn cheque.

David Craig Ellis , 41 , has admitted killing Alec Warburton , 59 , at a house in Sketty, Swansea. The incident took place at a property on Lon Masarn, where emergency services were called. Ellis pleaded guilty to manslaughter at Swansea Crown Court, with the judge adjourning the case for sentencing. The court heard that Mr Warburton's death followed an altercation.

Mr Mills had been deputy chairman of the group designated the lead "out" campaign by the Electoral Commission.
He has previously claimed the campaign was torn by internal feuding.
He was reported to have been on the verge of quitting in February when Labour MP Kate Hoey joined a rival out campaign.
In his resignation letter, the home shopping magnate said he had "come to believe that it would be useful and more effective for the Leave campaign if there was a strong and independent Labour voice for the arguments to leave the EU".
"I can now focus fully on my role as ... director of Labour Leave, and create that distinctive voice," he said.
"In the run up to the vote on 23 June, Labour Leave will provide a compelling and robust left-of-centre case for leaving the EU."
The vast majority of Labour MPs are in favour of Britain remaining in the EU - with about a dozen campaigning for an exit.
Labour former minister Frank Field has warned the party it risks losing "a swathe" of voters to UKIP by campaigning to remain in the EU.
Mr Mills, who played a leading role in the 1975 referendum campaign against EU membership, has also been critical of Jeremy Corbyn's decision to back staying in.
He said: "I hope this decision will be a transformative first step to motivating Labour people who are still unsure how they will vote, to vote Leave in June to secure a better, fairer future for this country.
"Labour Leave will continue to work with Vote Leave, as well as other Leave campaigns across the piece, to secure a stronger future for the UK outside the EU."
Vote Leave was the organisation chosen by the Electoral Commission to take the lead in making the case for Britain to leave the European Union. It is headed by big Conservative names Boris Johnson and Michael Gove and Labour MP Gisela Stuart with support from Lib Dem and UKIP figures, as well as business people.
Subscribe to the BBC News EU referendum email newsletter and get a weekly round-up of news, features and analysis on the campaign sent straight to your inbox.

Star Randel-Hanson killed Derick Marney, 70, at a flat in Vernon Terrace, Brighton, in May 2015.
He broke down and confessed to the murder 10 days later he went to tarot reader Jayne Braiden on Brighton seafront.
She alerted police but was told it was a "non-emergency" so she waited an hour with the killer for an officer to come.
Ms Braiden told BBC Radio 5 Live: "By the time we got to the devil card he broke down and started crying.
"It's the first time I've dealt with murder before. It was a shock but you have to be professional and I needed to keep him calm."
Mr Marney died from a six-inch (15cm) stab wound to his side, which punctured his vital organs.
Sussex Police said it was "not clear" what motivated Randel-Hanson - who was jailed for life on 9 May - to carry out the murder.
After gaining the defendant's trust, Ms Braiden asked him whether she could go outside to call the police. He agreed.
She said: "I explained [to the 999 operator] I was a tarot reader and told her a man had confessed to murder.
"She told me it was a non-priority call and I needed to ring the non-emergency number.
"Unfortunately they didn't believe me, but I'm not surprised at that."
She said she then bought Randel-Hanson a drink from a shop next door and waited 55 minutes for police to arrive.
"I asked him if it was ok if I took notes... I took names, places, where he had been stabbed and where the body was," she said.
"I didn't ask him why, and to be fair I don't think he wanted to talk to me about that.
"We joked about the time it took the police to come.
"He was getting tense at that point as I was not only looking for police through the glass doors, he was as well."
Sussex Police later admitted the call had been given the wrong level of priority.
A spokesman said it has been discussed with the call handler concerned and "suitable advice was given".

The swoon weighed on US markets, offsetting gains in financial and energy stocks.
The tech-heavy Nasdaq index fell 113.84 points or 1.80%% to 6,207.92.
The broader S&P 500 dipped 2.02 points or 0.08% to 2,431.77, while the Dow Jones edged up 89.44 points, rising 0.42% to 21,271.97.
US markets had seen limited movement earlier this week, as markets waited to see the results of the UK election and reaction to the testimony by former FBI director James Comey in Washington.
Mr Trump's firing of Mr Comey, who had been leading the FBI investigation into ties between Russia and the Trump campaign, has drawn a political backlash, threatening the prospects for key business initiatives in Washington.
But the testimony contained little new information and Republicans appeared confident in plans to press forward on key initiatives, such as loosening financial rules.
Financial stocks gained nearly 2% on Friday, while energy stocks rose more than 2% as oil prices stabilised.
But those increases couldn't overcome the fall in technology stocks.
Netflix fell 4.7%, Apple sank 3.9%, Google-owner Alphabet dropped 3.4% Facebook declined 3.3% and Amazon fell 3.2%.
The firms' weeks of success on Wall Street had won it an acronym - FAANG - and led to a steady drumbeat of commentary about possibly inflated values, but it wasn't clear what triggered the widespread sell-off.
It wasn't all bad for internet companies.
Pandora shares jumped 1.2% on Friday, after the music streaming service said it would receive a $480m cash infusion from Sirius XM.
Pandora said the investment by Sirius XM, a satellite radio company, would give it money to grow. It also gives Sirius exposure to the market for online radio.

Police were called to a break - in at a house in the Shiregreen area of the city on Monday . The victim is in " a stable condition in hospital after suffering injuries during the violent break-in. South Yorkshire Police are investigating the incident, which occurred just after midnight. Detective Inspector Paul Wilson, leading the inquiry, said: 'This was a distressing incident for the homeowner. We are appealing for anyone who saw anything suspicious in the Shiregreen area around that time to come forward. Any information, no matter how small, could be crucial to our investigation. We are committed to bringing those responsible for this break to justice.' Officers have conducted house-to-house inquiries and are reviewing CCTV footage from the surrounding area as part of their ongoing efforts to trace the offenders.

Andreea Cristea is the fifth victim of the attack on 22 March , in which Khalid Masood drove into crowds on Westminster Bridge then stabbed a policeman to death , before being shot dead himself . Ms Cristea , 31 , who was on holiday with boyfriend Andrei Burnaz , had been in hospital since the attack . It has emerged that Mr Burnaz had been planning to propose during the day out . A family statement confirmed Ms Cristea , who was an architect , had died on Thursday . The architect, who had been visiting London from Romania, was thrown into the River Thames during the rampage by Khalid Masood. She was rescued from the water but had suffered catastrophic head injuries and a severe lung infection, remaining in critical condition for weeks at St Thomas' Hospital. Her family, including her parents and sister, had maintained a constant vigil at her bedside, desperately hoping for her recovery, until her tragic passing.

Mr Burnaz, who sustained a fractured foot in the attack and has since undergone surgery, has spoken emotionally about the terrifying moments after they were hit and his desperate search for Andreea amidst the chaos. He described seeing Ms Cristea disappear into the water after being struck by the vehicle, and his frantic efforts to locate her before she was pulled out by rescuers. The couple, originally from Constanța, Romania, were on a romantic trip, and the revelation that Mr Burnaz had intended to propose adds a profoundly tragic layer to their story, highlighting the dreams and future abruptly stolen by the act of terror.

Ms Cristea's death tragically brings the total number of fatalities directly resulting from Khalid Masood's attack to five. The other victims were US tourist Kurt Cochran, retired window cleaner Leslie Rhodes, and mother-of-two Aysha Frade, all of whom were struck on Westminster Bridge, along with PC Keith Palmer, the brave officer stabbed to death by Masood at the gates of the Palace of Westminster. The attack, which stunned the world, transformed a bustling London landmark into a scene of unimaginable horror and grief.

Tributes have poured in for Andreea, remembering her as a vibrant, talented architect with a promising future. The Romanian Ambassador to the UK expressed deep sorrow, conveying the shared grief of the Romanian community for her loss. Her tragic passing is a stark reminder of the global reach of such violence, impacting individuals from diverse backgrounds who were simply enjoying a day out in a major capital. The investigation into Masood’s motives and potential associates continues, but the devastating human cost of his actions, epitomized by Ms Cristea and Mr Burnaz, remains the most poignant legacy. London, a city known for its enduring spirit and resilience, mourns its lost, but remains united against the hatred that seeks to divide it.

Britain 's world heavyweight champion apologised last month for a video he posted online containing homophobic , sexist and anti - Semitic comments . But ex - champion Klitschko , who fights Fury in Manchester on 9 July , said : " I was in shock at his statements . " When I heard about the video, I found it incredibly disturbing," the Ukrainian fighter continued, clearly upset. "As a professional athlete, you have a responsibility to be a role model. To use your platform for such hateful rhetoric, especially anti-Semitic comments that evoke dark periods of history, is simply unacceptable. It goes against everything sport should represent." Klitschko, himself from a nation that suffered immensely during World War II, expressed deep concern about the impact such statements could have.

Fury’s controversial remarks had drawn widespread condemnation across Britain, leading to calls for his license to be revoked. His anti-Semitic tirade, in which he claimed "Zionist, Jewish people... own all the banks, all the palaces, all the world," caused profound offence, echoing historical prejudices. His previous sexist and homophobic comments also resurfaced, painting a picture of ingrained bigotry. The Campaign Against Antisemitism, a prominent UK watchdog, was particularly vocal, calling for decisive action against the British boxer. They emphasized the danger of hateful speech from high-profile athletes, especially when it mirrors rhetoric associated with figures like Hitler, stressing the need for public figures to grasp the gravity of their words. Klitschko added, "This isn't just about boxing anymore. This is about basic human decency and respect." He stressed that while the fight was imminent, Fury’s actions had transcended the sport, raising serious questions about a champion's values. The immense backlash forced Fury to issue an apology, which many found insincere, only fueling the controversy.

The visitors closed on 293 - 9 at the end of day three , with a lead of 260 . Jacques Rudolph 's wait for a first Championship hundred in 2016 continued as he chopped onto his stumps for 56 . Earlier , Essex had been bowled out for 319 , with Craig Meschede ( 5 - 84 ) taking his first five - wicket haul in first-class cricket for Glamorgan. His accurate seam bowling ripped through the Essex middle order, claiming the crucial scalps of Simon Harmer and Neil Wagner as Essex were dismissed for 319. Earlier, Alastair Cook had made a patient 90, but Meschede's spell truly restricted Essex.

Glamorgan began their second innings with a 26-run deficit. Openers Nick Selman (41) and Jacques Rudolph built a steady platform. Rudolph, despite his eventual dismissal, looked largely untroubled for much of his 125-ball stay, striking seven boundaries. His uncharacteristic lapse saw him drag a delivery from Jamie Porter onto his stumps, ending his aspirations of a century. His departure at 110 for 2 brought Marnus Labuschagne (28) to the crease, who was then trapped lbw by Sam Cook. The Glamorgan middle order faced a testing period. Chris Cooke battled for his 35, and Kiran Carlson added 22, but wickets fell regularly as Essex bowlers exploited the variable bounce. A late cameo from Ryan Thomas, who hit a valuable 18 not out, helped extend the lead as the light faded. The visitors will hope their tailenders can add valuable runs on day four to set Essex a challenging target, with the pitch showing signs of wear and tear, promising more assistance for the spinners. Rudolph's earlier efforts, alongside Meschede's disciplined bowling, have put Glamorgan in a strong position, but the final day promises to be tense. The match remains finely poised, with Glamorgan holding the upper hand thanks to their consistent batting and Meschede's destructive spell.

Logan Murdoch suffered serious injuries in the crash and was not breathing when the Great North Air Ambulance team arrived . Hayley Murdoch , 29 , and Sheila Dixon , 71 , both from Carlisle , died following the collision at Newby Cross in 2016 . Dr Laura Duffy called Logan , years after that harrowing day, to marvel at his incredible journey back to health. She vividly recalled the scene at Newby Cross, describing it as one of the most challenging she had ever encountered. Logan had been clinically dead, but through the swift, coordinated efforts of the emergency services – the first responders, paramedics, and the air ambulance crew – he was resuscitated at the roadside. He was then airlifted to the Royal Victoria Infirmary in Newcastle in a critical condition, placed in an induced coma, and remained there for several weeks, fighting for his life. His family, already reeling from the devastating loss of Hayley Murdoch and Sheila Dixon, braced themselves for the worst, enduring agonizing days and nights by his bedside.

Against all odds, Logan began a slow, arduous recovery. Dr Duffy recounted the initial prognosis, which had been bleak, suggesting severe brain damage and long-term disability were highly probable. Yet, Logan’s resilience and determination, coupled with exceptional medical care, defied these expectations. His rehabilitation was extensive, involving months of physiotherapy, speech therapy, and psychological support to help him come to terms with the traumatic event and the profound grief of losing his mother and grandmother. The call from Dr Duffy was a poignant reminder of how close he came to joining them. She told him that his survival was nothing short of miraculous, a testament to the life-saving work done in those critical moments at the crash site near Carlisle. Logan, now a vocal advocate for the Great North Air Ambulance, often reflects on that day, acknowledging that without their rapid response, he would not be here today to share his story or remember his beloved Hayley Murdoch and Sheila Dixon. The scars, both physical and emotional, remain, but so does an immense gratitude for the second chance at life he received.

Stefan Appleton, 18, was with friends when he was attacked in Nightingale Park in Islington on 10 June last year.
The killer stabbed him with the 25in (63cm) serrated blade after leaping off a stolen moped, the Old Bailey heard.
The 17-year-old, who cannot be named due to his age, was cleared of murder. He will be sentenced on 21 April.
Mr Appleton, a college student from Islington, had been with friends when his attacker jumped off the back of a scooter, pulled out the weapon and chased after the victim and his friends, the jury heard.
He was stabbed repeatedly after tripping and falling. The cause of his death was shock and haemorrhage due to a stab wound to the chest, police said.
The Metropolitan Police has issued guidance about 'zombie' knives, advising that this is how certain ornate knives are currently being marketed. The force says:
Children were playing in the park at the time of the attack.
As the killer was ridden from the scene, the court heard he shouted out "RP" - standing for Red Pitch, a rival to a gang in the Nightingale Park area.
The alleged getaway rider, 17, was cleared of murder while another boy, also 17, was found not guilty of conspiracy to cause grievous bodily harm.
After the machete attack, the killer fled to Bristol and tried to fly to Malaga in Spain, but was arrested when he returned to London to lie low.
In his defence, the killer said he had come under attack when he went to snatch back his bicycle which had been stolen by another boy.
The court heard he had a previous conviction for possessing a blade after being caught with a lock-knife in a McDonald's restaurant a year before the killing.
Prosecutor Simon Denison QC said Mr Appleton's death was another "tragic waste of a young life" taken by a knife.
Speaking after the conviction, Det Ch Insp Chris Jones said: "There can be absolutely no excuse for young people to carry such dreadful weapons on London's streets and this case once again highlights the awful consequences of doing so."

Lachlan returns to the Murdoch empire as co-chairman of News Corp and 21st Century Fox, having previously stood back to focus on his own businesses.
Meanwhile, younger son James was appointed co-chief operating officer at 21st Century Fox.
After the phone hacking scandal, James quit as executive chairman of News International in 2012.
News Corp is one of the world's biggest media organisations, and owns newspaper titles The Times, Sun, and the Wall Street Journal.
News Corp split from 21st Century Fox in 2013. The business owns broadcaster Fox News in the US and British Sky Broadcasting in the UK.
Rupert Murdoch, who went through a high-profile split with wife Wendi Deng last year, said Lachlan was a "talented executive" with a "rich" knowledge of the business.
Lachlan will report to Chase Carey, chief executive at 21st Century Fox.
Rupert said: "I am very pleased he is returning to a leadership role at the company, where he will look closely with me, Chase, James and rest of the board of directors to drive continued growth for years to come."
He also said he was "pleased" to promote James into the "important role".
There is reportedly no new role for the third sibling, Elisabeth Murdoch, however, who sought to distance herself from James after the phone hacking scandal.

6 October 2016 Last updated at 16:36 BST More than 500 students in South Africa have joined nationwide protests over rising university fees, according to reports monitored by BBC Africa, continuing a movement that began earlier this October.

The Caerau hill fort near Ely is thought to have been occupied from the 5th Century BC by the Silurian tribe.
A dig last year involving 1,000 people found its use may have continued into the late Roman era or even later.
The Caerau And Ely Rediscovering Heritage (Caer) Project runs until 25 July.
Organisers say work on the site since 2011 has helped rewrite the history of early Cardiff, revealing an early occupation date for a hill fort with "massive" ramparts.
Last year's excavations revealed:
Caer Heritage Project co-director Olly Davis said: "During the 2013 dig, more than 1,000 local people visited the dig while it was happening, and 120 more were directly involved in the archaeological work.
"Our challenge this year is to attract twice as many visitors and to get the people of South Wales to value this amazing site and celebrate the remarkable communities which live in its shadow."

Up to 40,000 people and 140 bands took part in the march, which is the largest loyal order demonstration in Northern Ireland.
Three people have been arrested for public order offences.
The event began with a parade around the city's historic walls and was followed by a wreath laying ceremony at the War Memorial in the Diamond.
A religious service was also held in St Columb's Cathedral.
PSNI Supt Mark McEwan praised all sides for working together to ensure the parade was peaceful.
"There haven't been any problems today at all, the operation has been a success," he said.
"Everyone seems to have been enjoying a good day out. The feeling and atmosphere in the city is one of festivity."
Jim Brownlee, governor of the Apprentice Boys of Derry, said the emphasis within the Apprentice Boys was on respect.
"That's still down to every member of this association especially when we're on parade and in the public domain," he said.
"We want people to respect this parade and we want the people on parade to respect the people who will either be watching it or commenting upon it."
A pageant re-enacting the Siege of Derry took place ahead of the start of the main parade.

Armed troops are already being deployed to protect key locations such as Buckingham Palace, Downing Street and embassies to free up police officers.
It comes after the bomb attack at Manchester Arena on Monday which killed 22 people, some as young as eight.
London mayor Sadiq Khan said security experts were advising event organisers.
He said there was "no reason to be alarmed or to panic, this is a prudent course to take".
Bomber 'likely' not acting alone
Manchester attack: The next steps for police and MI5
The mayor added he was in close contact with Met Police Commissioner Cressida Dick and the force had assured him they have all the resources they need.
The decision to replace police officers with soldiers at key public locations was taken at a meeting of the government's emergency Cobra committee on Tuesday.
After the announcement the national security threat level was raised to critical and the Palace of Westminster shut to the public.
All tours and events due to take place there have been cancelled with immediate effect.
A man with a knife was arrested outside Buckingham Palace earlier, shortly before the Queen was driven along the Mall. The Met has said the incident is not terror-related.
The FA Cup final between Arsenal and Chelsea takes place at Wembley on Saturday - the final day of the Chelsea Flower Show.
Commander Jane Connors, leading the London policing operation, said: "We will do all we can to protect the capital at this unsettling time. All our work is designed to make our city as hostile an environment as possible for terrorists to plan and operate."
Other measures being taken include an increase in armed officers to provide support for uniformed and undercover officers trying to spot people carrying out "hostile reconnaissance" and other criminal activity in London.
The tactic is "based on extensive research into the psychology of criminals and what undermines their activities", the force said.
There will also be an increase in the use of stop and search, vehicle check points and number plate recognition technology.
"The reality is we must be prepared to be able to respond to and deal with armed and deadly attackers, so we must be in a position to respond with firearms officers who will use force to stop those attackers in their aim," added Ms Connors.

In 2014, Kim Lennon said the smuggling of drugs was rife at Lewes Prison and its wings "resembled a war zone".
She was dismissed earlier this week following disciplinary proceedings but said she would appeal and had no regrets about speaking out.
The Ministry of Justice (MoJ) said Ms Lennon was not dismissed for being a whistleblower.
'Insufficient staff'
Ms Lennon alleged in August 2014 that the drug Spice was being smuggled into the jail.
She said officers were supposed to carry out daily cell checks but there were insufficient staff to do so, and that she feared an inmate or prison officer would be seriously injured.
The Prison Service denied at the time that staffing levels were unsafe and said there was a "zero-tolerance approach" to illicit substances.
Ms Lennon was suspended from her job after talking to the The Argus newspaper and the BBC.
"Speaking out has caused me a lot of distress but I don't regret it," she said. "Frontline prison officers are too afraid to speak out because of what will happen to them."
"I loved my job and I feel like I am being punished for doing the right thing," she said.
"I am going to appeal but I'm taking it one day at a time."
The MoJ said it could not comment because Ms Lennon's dismissal was a confidential matter.
"We would not wish to prejudice a possible appeal," it said in a statement, adding it took the issue of staff discipline extremely seriously.
"Any unprofessional behaviour will be investigated immediately, with strong action taken and serious wrongdoing referred to the police," it said.
"Disciplinary action can range from a verbal warning to dismissal from their post."

That is according to new figures from Northern Ireland Screen, which has provided production funding for the HBO series.
The programme, some of which is filmed in Northern Ireland, has been nominated for 24 Emmy awards.
Two of those nominations are for Northern Ireland production crew members.
Ronan Hill, who won an Emmy in 2012, has been nominated again for outstanding sound mixing for a drama, while Carla Stronge has been nominated for outstanding casting for a drama.
Northern Ireland Screen has invested ¬£12.45m in the series since it began in 2010.
For that investment, it is estimated that ¬£110.7m has been spent on goods and services in the Northern Ireland economy.
From 2010-14, Game of Thrones brought in between ¬£21m and ¬£23m a year to Northern Ireland. Those figures have been audited.
In 2014-15, in which series five of Game of Thrones was filmed, NI Screen invested ¬£1.6m in the programme, and the return that created is estimated at ¬£22m.
Game of Thrones is filmed at the Titanic Studios in Belfast, and many other locations across Northern Ireland.
Many local companies are involved in providing services when the series is in production, and sites from the show have become tourist attractions.
Damian Carr, from Game of Thrones Tours, said fans come from all over the world to visit the filming locations.
"We've had people from North and South America, all over Asia - China, Japan, Korea, Taiwan - and all across Europe.
"We started off running one tour a week; now we're running five."
Richard Williams, chief executive of NI Screen, said Game of Thrones had established Northern Ireland as a world-class location for film and TV production.
"Additionally, films and television programmes have a significant, positive effect on tourism; they contribute to a wider 'branding' of people, society and culture, all of which has a very strong influence on creating a desire to travel.
"There is no doubt that Game of Thrones is spearheading this set-jetting phenomenon and we have made no secret of the fact that we hope the show will do for Northern Ireland what Lord of the Rings did for New Zealand," he said.

The suspects are accused of smuggling large quantities of cocaine from Colombia to Europe in sailing boats.
Officials said among those arrested is a commander of the Colombian left-wing rebel group, Farc.
Police said the suspects were part of a transatlantic drugs ring run by the 'Ndrangheta crime syndicate, which has its base in southern Italy.
The investigation, dubbed Santa Fe, was carried out jointly by Italian agents, members of the US Drug Enforcement Administration and Spain's Guardia Civil.
Officials said the drug ring operated in countries as far flung as Argentina, Brazil, Colombia, Dominican Republic, Spain and Montenegro.
The identity of the Farc commander has not yet been made public, but Colombian media said it would soon be revealed.
The rebel group derives much of its finances from cocaine production and trafficking.
Officials said that in the course of their investigations they seized a total of four tonnes of cocaine.
One of the largest seizures was in the night of 25-26 August last year when the Spanish navy stopped a sailboat heading for the Italian coast.
They found 856kg of cocaine on board.
They said that the drugs were smuggled from Colombia mainly into southern Italian port of Gioia Tauro in Calabria, but that they were also taken to ports in northern Italy such as Vado Ligure, Livorno and Genoa.
Police say the 'Ndrangheta operates the biggest cocaine smuggling network in Europe.

The girl was walking with a woman , aged 55 , when they were suddenly struck by a black Ford Fiesta turning sharply from Lugsmore Lane onto Dunriding Lane. The woman was thrown to the ground, while the girl managed to jump out of the way, narrowly avoiding serious injury. Emergency services were immediately called to the scene.

A report has said uniting council departments with different responsibilities would help improve the town's prospects.
The strategy aims to reduce the number of empty shop units, increase visitors with more public events and reduce antisocial behaviour.
It is being discussed at a council meeting on Wednesday afternoon.
Town centre forum business group chairman Andrew Atkinson welcomed the report and said it could lead to be a "huge turnaround for Wrexham".
The report highlights how one department looks after town centre economic strategy while others deal with cleaning up the streets or looking after licensing and public protection issues although they share a common goal.
It recommends a single group taking forward all issues that tackle town centre improvements.
Mr Atkinson said: "It has got to be action and not words from the council."
He said the authority was taking positive steps with shops' vacancy rates reducing due to more independent shops opening, but he admitted bigger units formerly occupied by multi national firms were "harder to fill".
This month, work started on a ¬£4.5m development at Wrexham's People's Market to incorporate an arts centre.

The statement from the firm came just days after it announced the sale of the Financial Times to Japan's Nikkei.
Pearson said it was in discussions regarding the sale of the Economist but there was "no certainty that this process will lead to a transaction".
It did not name the potential buyers, but Italy's Agnelli family said it was in talks to increase its holding.
Exor, the investment arm of the Agnelli family, currently holds a 4.72% stake in the Economist Group.
The firm said on its website that any increased investment would "represent a minority shareholding in the the Economist... reflecting Exor's strong commitment to the editorial independence that lies at the heart of the Economist's ethos and success".
It also stressed that there was no certainty of a deal.
Other Economist shareholders include the family dynasties Cadbury, Rothschild and Schroder.
The Financial Times reported that the 50% stake was valued at √Ç¬£400m and that the sale was likely to be concluded over the summer.
The Economist Group includes in the Economist magazine, the research company the Economist Intelligence Unit and the US legislative information provider CQ Roll Call.
On Thursday Pearson agreed to sell the Financial Times for √Ç¬£844m as part of the group's strategy to focus just on education.

Zdenko Turtak, who was extradited from Slovakia, had previously admitted rape and grievous bodily harm.
Turtak attacked his victim at a bus stop in Beeston Road in March before dragging her behind a hedge and raping her. He later fled the UK.
He will be sentenced on 19 October at Leeds Crown Court.
Prosecutors did not to pursue the attempted murder charge at Leeds Crown Court on Thursday.

The star of How I Met Your Mother and Gone Girl will host 10 episodes of the variety show for NBC, according to the Hollywood Reporter.
Harris called the show, created by British TV presenting duo Ant McPartlin and Declan Donnelly, "a game changer".
McPartlin, Donnelly and Harris will produce the yet-to-be named show, which is likely not to air on Saturdays.
The show, which pays homage to variety shows of the past, started in the UK in 2002.
It won two Bafta awards this year and there are versions in Germany, Portugal, Italy and Belgium.
The show features comedy sketches, song and dance numbers and audience interaction.
"As I watched the show, I couldn't stop smiling. Now that I've seen many seasons, my face hurts," Harris said.
"Its unique structure fits right into my random skill set. I can't wait to roll up my sleeves and have some fun."
Harris has just finished a run on Broadway in Hedwig and the Angry Inch and was recently announced as the host of the 2015 Oscars.
Last year he made his fourth appearance hosting the Tony Awards, drawing plaudits for his hosting duties and show-stopping opening number.

The 24-year-old, who cannot be named until he enters his plea, is accused of raping the teenager in the toilets of a bar in Johannesburg.
Earlier in the week, the family of the alleged victim said that Mr Mandela's ex-wife, Winnie Madikizela-Mandela, had sent her bodyguard to dissuade them from pressing charges.
The Mandela family has not commented.
Senior members of the Mandela family, including the former president's daughter Makaziwe Mandela, were in court during a brief hearing.
His bail application has been postponed until Tuesday, meaning he cannot legally be named until then.
He has been in custody since his arrest on Saturday.
The BBC understands that he will argue that it was consensual sex and he didn't know that his accuser was underage since the pub did not allow under-21s on its premises.
Under South African law, sex with someone under 16 is classed as rape whether consensual or not.
BBC Southern Africa correspondent Karen Allen says the family of South Africa's first black president have found themselves constantly in the public spotlight.
Just three months ago, another of his grandsons, Mandla Mandela, was given a suspended sentence after being convicted of assault, following an attack on a teacher after a road rage incident.

Members of Braintree's Dolphin Women's Institute (WI) have stitched some of the town's best-known landmarks including the church and museum.
Each model is about 45cm (18in) tall and was created using a polystyrene or cardboard core with knitting sewn on.
It took nine knitters seven months to complete the seven miniature buildings which will be displayed at the town's museum next month.
The group's vice-president, Elaine Pye, said the project was inspired by a similar one a relative had been involved in knitting in Hertfordshire.
"They knitted their own cottages, but we couldn't really do that so chose some of the town's beautiful iconic buildings," she said.
Mrs Pye put together the polystyrene structures and each knitter got to work, returning after two weeks with their latest knitted piece of church spire or pub frontage.
After much gluing, sewing and additional knitted embellishments, the town finally took shape, brought together with mini woollen market stalls.
The group created models of the town hall, church, Swan pub, library, museum, shopping centre and even the railway station complete with knitted train.
"It really brought everyone together and the response has been amazing," Mrs Pye said.
"So much so that they want to do more, so we think we might knit the Public Gardens next."

A total of 374 employees lost their jobs when Tullis Russell Papermakers, based at Markinch in Fife, went into administration in April 2015.
Each employee received the equivalent of eight weeks' wages in compensation for their loss.
The award follows a judgement from an employment tribunal in Dundee.
Lawyers said that despite the company directors being under an obligation to provide employees with at least 45 days' notice - as more than 100 workers were losing their jobs - this was ignored, meaning each employee was entitled to sue for compensation.
However, acting alone would have meant each affected worker lodging "an extremely complex" and expensive employment tribunal claim, so they made a joint bid.
David Martyn, a senior employment lawyer at Thompsons, the firm that represented the workers, said: "The more notice the workforce have to prepare for these devastating changes, the better they can organise their financial responsibilities to soften the blow.
"This award of compensation will be paid by UK administration service.
"That means that the taxpayer has picked up the tab because company directors have played fast and loose with the rules.
"This has to stop and I believe we need to see more criminal prosecutions of companies that behave this way."
Paul Reilly, Unite branch secretary said: "This is a great result for my members and it goes a long way towards the hurt that happened."

The move follows a rise in the number of oil and gas operators using unmanned aerial systems (UAS) to conduct inspections and other offshore tasks.
The guidelines were developed by industry and aviation safety experts and UAS operators.
They cover best practice, procedures and the certification needed to be compliant with UAS regulations.
Oil and Gas UK's health, safety and environment director Mick Borwell said: "A small but increasing number of oil and gas operators are using UAS for inspections predominantly, but also for aerial photography, surveying and security.
"The technology is particularly attractive for its use in improving safety.
"For example, sending unmanned aircraft instead of people into confined spaces to conduct inspections reduces risk, and is also effective and efficient.
"We expect their usage to grow."
Mr Borwell said the new guidelines aimed to be consistent with safety and operating standards already adopted on the UK Continental Shelf for offshore oil and gas production and helicopter flight operations.
He added: "The intention is to encourage offshore operators planning on using this emerging technology to think about the whole operating and safety system offshore and not just the air vehicle."

Powell, 21, featured 16 times last year and played in the season opener loss to Huddersfield, and a warm-up match against New Zealand Warriors.
